// Single ton Class;

public class Singelton{
private final static Singleton instance = new Singleton();
private Singleton(){}
public static Singleton getInstance(){
return instance;
}
}

=========== Second Type ==========

public class Singleton{
private static Singleton instance;
private Singleton(){}
public static Singleton getInstance(){
if(instance == null){
instance = new Singleton();
}
return instance;
}
}

public class Singleton {
private static Singleton instance;
private Singleton(){}
public static synchronized Singleton getInstance(){
if(instance == null){
instance = new Singleton();
}
return instance;
}


public class Singleton {
private static Singleton instance;
private Singleton(){}
public static Singleton getInstance(){
if(instance == null){
synchronized (Singleton.class){
if(instance == null){
instance = new Singleton();
}
}
}
return instance;
}
}

why are there different types of singleton implementations?
Different types of singleton implementations exist to address various requirements and constraints, such as thread safety, performance, and resource management. Here are some reasons for the different implementations:
1. Eager Initialization: This implementation creates the singleton instance at the time of class loading. It
is simple and thread-safe but may lead to resource wastage if the instance is never used.
2. Lazy Initialization: This implementation creates the singleton instance only when it is needed. It saves resources but requires additional synchronization to ensure thread safety.
3. Thread Safety: In multi-threaded environments, it is crucial to ensure that only one instance of the singleton is created. Different implementations use various synchronization techniques to achieve this, such as synchronized
methods or double-checked locking.
4. Performance: Some implementations prioritize performance by minimizing synchronization overhead, especially in high-concurrency scenarios.
5. Serialization: Some singleton implementations need to handle serialization and deserialization to ensure that the singleton property is maintained across different states.
Overall, the choice of singleton implementation depends on the specific use cases and requirements of the application.



